    "summary": {
      "background": "Deeper neural networks are more difficult to train, and a degradation problem has been observed where accuracy saturates and then degrades rapidly with increasing depth, which is not caused by overfitting. This paper addresses this degradation problem by introducing a deep residual learning framework.",
      "contributions": [
        "Proposes a residual learning framework that reformulates layers as learning residual functions with reference to layer inputs, making it easier to optimize deeper networks.",
        "Demonstrates that residual networks (ResNets) can gain accuracy from considerably increased depth, achieving state-of-the-art results on ImageNet with depths up to 152 layers.",
        "Wins 1st place in ILSVRC 2015 classification, detection, localization, COCO detection, and COCO segmentation competitions.",
        "Provides comprehensive empirical evidence on ImageNet and CIFAR-10 showing that ResNets overcome the degradation problem and are easier to optimize than plain networks."
      ],
      "methodology": "The core method introduces shortcut connections that perform identity mapping, adding the input of a stack of layers to their output, effectively learning residual functions F(x) = H(x) - x instead of the original mapping H(x). These identity shortcuts add no extra parameters or computational complexity, and the entire network can be trained end-to-end with SGD and backpropagation.",
      "experiments": "Experiments are conducted on ImageNet 2012 classification (1.28M training images, 50k validation, 100k test) and CIFAR-10 (50k training, 10k testing). Baselines include plain networks of varying depths, VGG nets, GoogLeNet, and Highway networks. For ImageNet, ResNets with 18, 34, 50, 101, and 152 layers are evaluated; for CIFAR-10, depths of 20, 32, 44, 56, 110, and 1202 layers are tested.",
      "results": "On ImageNet, the 152-layer ResNet achieves a single-model top-5 error of 4.49% and an ensemble top-5 error of 3.57%, outperforming all previous methods. On CIFAR-10, the 110-layer ResNet achieves 6.43% test error, and the 1202-layer network shows no optimization difficulty but slightly higher test error due to overfitting. ResNets consistently outperform plain networks of the same depth, demonstrating that residual learning effectively addresses the degradation problem.",
      "limitations": "The 1202-layer ResNet on CIFAR-10 shows worse test error than the 110-layer network, attributed to overfitting due to the model's large size relative to the dataset. The paper notes that stronger regularization (e.g., maxout or dropout) could improve results but was not used to focus on optimization difficulties. Additionally, the optimization difficulty of deep plain nets is not fully explained and is left for future study."
    },
